---
Midgaard's Violet Compact has classified the oathbroken designation as a functionally equivalent analog to Midgaard's charter-revocation proceedings: institution loses charter, officers lose legal standing, reinstatement requires demonstrated remediation.
Midgaard's difference: revocation requires a formal judicial hearing before designation, while Khardaan's classification could be issued by a commanding officer during active crisis.
This difference matters because several Khardaan oathbroken designations were issued by officers who themselves were later found to have violated custody obligations.
The Reckoning faction argues that if Midgaard treats Khardaan precedent as valid, it must apply Midgaard's evidentiary standards consistently, including to disputed designations.
The question is academically unresolved; it has not produced active litigation because there are no surviving parties with standing to contest the designations.

